# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vpn-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In computing, **Internet Protocol Security** (**IPsec**) is a secure network protocol suite that authenticates and encrypts packets of data to provide secure encrypted communication between two computers over an Internet Protocol network.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] It is used in virtual private networks (VPNs).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec includes protocols for establishing mutual authentication between agents at the beginning of a session and negotiation of cryptographic keys to use during the session.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec can protect data flows between a pair of hosts (*host-to-host*), between a pair of security gateways (*network-to-network*), or between a security gateway and a host (*network-to-host*).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec uses cryptographic security services to protect communications over Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] It supports network-level peer authentication, data origin authentication, data integrity, data confidentiality (encryption), and protection from replay attacks.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Starting in the early 1970s, the Advanced Research Projects Agency sponsored a series of experimental ARPANET encryption devices, at first for native ARPANET packet encryption and subsequently for TCP/IP packet encryption; some of these were certified and fielded.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] From 1986 to 1991, the NSA sponsored the development of security protocols for the Internet under its Secure Data Network Systems (SDNS) program.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] This brought together various vendors including Motorola who produced a network encryption device in 1988.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The work was openly published from about 1988 by NIST and, of these, *Security Protocol at Layer 3* (SP3) would eventually morph into the ISO standard Network Layer Security Protocol (NLSP).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In 1992, the US Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) was funded by DARPA CSTO to implement IPv6 and to research and implement IP encryption in 4.4 BSD, supporting both SPARC and x86 CPU architectures.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] DARPA made its implementation freely available via MIT.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Under NRL's DARPA-funded research effort, NRL developed the IETF standards-track specifications (RFC 1825 through RFC 1827) for IPsec.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] NRL's IPsec implementation was described in their paper in the 1996 USENIX Conference Proceedings.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] NRL's open-source IPsec implementation was made available online by MIT and became the basis for most initial commercial implementations.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed the IP Security Working Group in 1992 to standardize openly specified security extensions to IP, called *IPsec*.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The NRL developed standards were published by the IETF as RFC 1825 through RFC 1827.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The initial IPv4 suite was developed with few security provisions.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] As a part of the IPv4 enhancement, IPsec is a layer 3 OSI model or internet layer end-to-end security scheme.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The Security Authentication Header (AH) was developed at the US Naval Research Laboratory in the early 1990s and is derived in part from previous IETF standards' work for authentication of the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) version 2.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Authentication Header (AH) is a member of the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] AH ensures connectionless integrity by using a hash function and a secret shared key in the AH algorithm.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] AH also guarantees the data origin by authenticating IP packets.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Optionally a sequence number can protect the IPsec packet's contents against replay attacks, using the sliding window technique and discarding old packets.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] AH operates directly on top of IP, using IP protocol number 51.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Type of the next header, indicating what upper-layer protocol was protected.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] For example, an AH value of 4 equals 3×(32-bit fixed-length AH fields) + 3×(32-bit ICV fields) − 2 and thus an AH value of 4 means 24 octets.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Although the size is measured in 4-octet units, the length of this header needs to be a multiple of 8 octets if carried in an IPv6 packet.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Reserved for future use (all zeroes until then).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] When replay detection is enabled, sequence numbers are never reused, because a new security association must be renegotiated before an attempt to increment the sequence number beyond its maximum value.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The IP Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) was developed at the Naval Research Laboratory starting in 1992 as part of a DARPA-sponsored research project, and was openly published by IETF SIPP Working Group drafted in December 1993 as a security extension for SIPP.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] This ESP was originally derived from the US Department of Defense SP3D protocol, rather than being derived from the ISO Network-Layer Security Protocol (NLSP).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The SP3D protocol specification was published by NIST in the late 1980s, but designed by the Secure Data Network System project of the US Department of Defense.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) is a member of the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] It provides origin authenticity through source authentication, data integrity through hash functions and confidentiality through encryption protection for IP packets.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] ESP also supports encryption-only and authentication-only configurations, but using encryption without authentication is strongly discouraged because it is insecure.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Unlike Authentication Header (AH), ESP in transport mode does not provide integrity and authentication for the entire IP packet.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] However, in tunnel mode, where the entire original IP packet is encapsulated with a new packet header added, ESP protection is afforded to the whole inner IP packet (including the inner header) while the outer header (including any outer IPv4 options or IPv6 extension headers) remains unprotected.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] ESP operates directly on top of IP, using IP protocol number 50.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] There is a separate counter kept for every security association.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The protected contents of the original IP packet, including any data used to protect the contents (e.g. an Initialisation Vector for the cryptographic algorithm).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] ) is used for dummy packets, which may be inserted in the stream, and which contents should be discarded.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The IPsec protocols use a security association, where the communicating parties establish shared security attributes such as algorithms and keys.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] As such, IPsec provides a range of options once it has been determined whether AH or ESP is used.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Before exchanging data, the two hosts agree on which symmetric encryption algorithm is used to encrypt the IP packet, for example AES or ChaCha20, and which hash function is used to ensure the integrity of the data, such as BLAKE2 or SHA256.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] These parameters are agreed for the particular session, for which a lifetime must be agreed and a session key.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The algorithm for authentication is also agreed before the data transfer takes place and IPsec supports a range of methods.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Authentication is possible through pre-shared key, where a symmetric key is already in the possession of both hosts, and the hosts send each other hashes of the shared key to prove that they are in possession of the same key.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec also supports public key encryption, where each host has a public and a private key, they exchange their public keys and each host sends the other a nonce encrypted with the other host's public key.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Alternatively if both hosts hold a public key certificate from a certificate authority, this can be used for IPsec authentication.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The security associations of IPsec are established using the Internet Security Association and Key Management Protocol (ISAKMP).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] ISAKMP is implemented by manual configuration with pre-shared secrets, Internet Key Exchange (IKE and IKEv2), Kerberized Internet Negotiation of Keys (KINK), and the use of IPSECKEY DNS records.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] RFC 5386 defines Better-Than-Nothing Security (BTNS) as an unauthenticated mode of IPsec using an extended IKE protocol.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Cremers, and others have used formal methods to identify various anomalies which exist in IKEv1 and also in IKEv2.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] A similar procedure is performed for an incoming packet, where IPsec gathers decryption and verification keys from the security association database.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] For IP multicast a security association is provided for the group, and is duplicated across all authorized receivers of the group.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] There may be more than one security association for a group, using different SPIs, thereby allowing multiple levels and sets of security within a group.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Indeed, each sender can have multiple security associations, allowing authentication, since a receiver can only know that someone knowing the keys sent the data.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Note that the relevant standard does not describe how the association is chosen and duplicated across the group; it is assumed that a responsible party will have made the choice.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] To ensure that the connection between two endpoints has not been interrupted, endpoints exchange keepalive messages at regular intervals, which can also be used to automatically reestablish a tunnel lost due to connection interruption.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Dead Peer Detection (DPD) is a method of detecting a dead Internet Key Exchange (IKE) peer.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The method uses IPsec traffic patterns to minimize the number of messages required to confirm the availability of a peer.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] DPD is used to reclaim the lost resources in case a peer is found dead and it is also used to perform IKE peer failover.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The IPsec protocols AH and ESP can be implemented in a host-to-host transport mode, as well as in a network tunneling mode.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In transport mode, only the payload of the IP packet is usually encrypted or authenticated.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The routing is intact, since the IP header is neither modified nor encrypted; however, when the authentication header is used, the IP addresses cannot be modified by network address translation, as this always invalidates the hash value.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The transport and application layers are always secured by a hash, so they cannot be modified in any way, for example by translating the port numbers.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] A means to encapsulate IPsec messages for NAT traversal (NAT-T) has been defined by RFC documents describing the NAT-T mechanism.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In tunnel mode, the entire IP packet is encrypted and authenticated.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] It is then encapsulated into a new IP packet with a new IP header.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Tunnel mode is used to create virtual private networks for network-to-network communications (e.g. between routers to link sites), host-to-network communications (e.g. remote user access) and host-to-host communications (e.g. private chat).
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The IPsec can be implemented in the IP stack of an operating system.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] This method of implementation is done for hosts and security gateways.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Various IPsec capable IP stacks are available from companies, such as HP or IBM.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] An alternative is so called bump-in-the-stack (BITS) implementation, where the operating system source code does not have to be modified.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Here IPsec is installed between the IP stack and the network drivers.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] This way operating systems can be retrofitted with IPsec.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] This method of implementation is also used for both hosts and gateways.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] However, when retrofitting IPsec the encapsulation of IP packets may cause problems for the automatic path MTU discovery, where the maximum transmission unit (MTU) size on the network path between two IP hosts is established.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] If a host or gateway has a separate cryptoprocessor, which is common in the military and can also be found in commercial systems, a so-called bump-in-the-wire (BITW) implementation of IPsec is possible.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] When IPsec is implemented in the kernel, the key management and ISAKMP/IKE negotiation is carried out from user space.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The NRL-developed and openly specified "PF_KEY Key Management API, Version 2" is often used to enable the application-space key management application to update the IPsec security associations stored within the kernel-space IPsec implementation.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Existing IPsec implementations usually include ESP, AH, and IKE version 2.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Existing IPsec implementations on Unix-like operating systems, for example, Solaris or Linux, usually include PF_KEY version 2.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Embedded IPsec can be used to ensure the secure communication among applications running over constrained resource systems with a small overhead.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec was developed in conjunction with IPv6 and was originally required to be supported by all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec is also optional for IPv4 implementations.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec is most commonly used to secure IPv4 traffic.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] IPsec protocols were originally defined in RFC 1825 through RFC 1829, which were published in 1995.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In 1998, these documents were superseded by RFC 2401 and RFC 2412 with a few incompatible engineering details, although they were conceptually identical.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In addition, a mutual authentication and key exchange protocol Internet Key Exchange (IKE) was defined to create and manage security associations.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In December 2005, new standards were defined in RFC 4301 and RFC 4309 which are largely a superset of the previous editions with a second version of the Internet Key Exchange standard IKEv2.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] These third-generation documents standardized the abbreviation of IPsec to uppercase "IP" and lowercase "sec".
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] "ESP" generally refers to RFC 4303, which is the most recent version of the specification.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Since mid-2008, an IPsec Maintenance and Extensions (ipsecme) working group is active at the IETF.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In 2013, as part of the Snowden leaks, it was revealed that the US National Security Agency had been actively working to "Insert vulnerabilities into commercial encryption systems, IT systems, networks, and endpoint communications devices used by targets" as part of the Bullrun program.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] There are allegations that IPsec was a targeted encryption system.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The OpenBSD IPsec stack came later on and also was widely copied.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In a letter which OpenBSD lead developer Theo de Raadt received on 11 Dec 2010 from Gregory Perry, it is alleged that Jason Wright and others, working for the FBI, inserted "a number of backdoors and side channel key leaking mechanisms" into the OpenBSD crypto code.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In the forwarded email from 2010, Theo de Raadt did not at first express an official position on the validity of the claims, apart from the implicit endorsement from forwarding the email.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Jason Wright's response to the allegations: "Every urban legend is made more real by the inclusion of real names, dates, and times.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Gregory Perry's email falls into this category. ...
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] I will state clearly that I did not add backdoors to the OpenBSD operating system or the OpenBSD Cryptographic Framework (OCF)." Some days later, de Raadt commented that "I believe that NETSEC was probably contracted to write backdoors as alleged. ...
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] If those were written, I don't believe they made it into our tree." This was published before the Snowden leaks.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] An alternative explanation put forward by the authors of the Logjam attack suggests that the NSA compromised IPsec VPNs by undermining the Diffie-Hellman algorithm used in the key exchange.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] In their paper, they allege the NSA specially built a computing cluster to precompute multiplicative subgroups for specific primes and generators, such as for the second Oakley group defined in RFC 2409.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] As of May 2015, 90% of addressable IPsec VPNs supported the second Oakley group as part of IKE.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] If an organization were to precompute this group, they could derive the keys being exchanged and decrypt traffic without inserting any software backdoors.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] The Cisco PIX and ASA firewalls had vulnerabilities that were used for wiretapping by the NSA.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] Furthermore, IPsec VPNs using "Aggressive Mode" settings send a hash of the PSK in the clear.
[src:vpn-security/ipsec] This can be and apparently is targeted by the NSA using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN allows peers to authenticate each other using pre-shared secret keys, certificates or username/password.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] When used in a multiclient-server configuration, it allows the server to release an authentication certificate for every client, using signatures and certificate authority.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It uses the OpenSSL encryption library extensively, as well as the TLS protocol, and contains many security and control features.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] As it uses a custom security protocol that utilizes SSL/TLS for key exchange.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It is capable of traversing network address translators (NATs) and firewalls.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN has been ported and embedded on several systems.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] For example, DD-WRT has the OpenVPN server function.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] SoftEther VPN, a multi-protocol VPN server, also has an implementation of the OpenVPN protocol.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It was written by James Yonan and is free software, released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Additionally, commercial licenses are available.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN uses the OpenSSL library to provide encryption of both the data and control channels.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It lets OpenSSL do all the encryption and authentication work, allowing OpenVPN to use all the ciphers available in the OpenSSL package.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It can also use the HMAC packet authentication feature to add an additional layer of security to the connection (referred to as an "HMAC Firewall" by the creator).
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It can also use hardware acceleration to get better encryption performance.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Support for mbed TLS is available starting from version 2.3.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN has several ways to authenticate peers with each other.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN offers pre-shared keys, certificate-based, and username/password-based authentication.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Preshared secret key is the easiest, and certificate-based is the most robust and feature-rich.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] In version 2.0, username/password authentications can be enabled, both with or without certificates.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] However, to make use of username/password authentications, OpenVPN depends on third-party modules.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN can run over User Datagram Protocol (UDP) or Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transports, multiplexing created SSL tunnels on a single TCP/UDP port (RFC 3948 for UDP).
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] From 2.3.x series on, OpenVPN fully supports IPv6 as a protocol of the virtual network inside a tunnel and the OpenVPN applications can also establish connections via IPv6.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It has the ability to work through most proxy servers (including HTTP) and is good at working through network address translation (NAT) and getting out through firewalls.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] The server configuration can "push" certain network configuration options to the clients.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] These include IP addresses, routing commands, and a few connection options.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN offers two types of interfaces for networking via the Universal TUN/TAP driver.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It can create either a layer-3 based IP tunnel (TUN), or a layer-2 based Ethernet TAP that can carry any type of Ethernet traffic.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN can optionally use the LZO compression library to compress the data stream.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Port 1194 is the official IANA assigned port number for OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Newer versions of the program now default to that port.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] A feature in the 2.0 version allows for one process to manage several simultaneous tunnels, as opposed to the original "one tunnel per process" restriction on the 1.x series.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN's use of common network protocols (TCP and UDP) makes it a desirable alternative to IPsec in situations where an ISP may block specific VPN protocols in order to force users to subscribe to a higher-priced, "business grade" service tier.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] For example, Comcast previously declared that their @Home product was, and had always been, designated as a residential service and did not allow the use of commercial applications.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Their argument was that conducting remote work via a VPN can adversely affect the network performance of their regular residential subscribers.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] They offered an alternative, @Home Professional, which would cost more than the @Home product.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] So, anyone wishing to use a VPN would have to subscribe to a higher-priced, business-grade service tier.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] When OpenVPN uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transports to establish a tunnel, performance will be acceptable only as long as there is sufficient excess bandwidth on the un-tunneled network link to guarantee that the tunneled TCP timers do not expire.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] If this becomes untrue, performance falls off dramatically due to the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN offers various internal security features.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It has up to 256-bit encryption through the OpenSSL library, although some service providers may offer lower rates, effectively providing some of the fastest VPN available to consumers.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN also supports Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS), which regenerates encryption keys at set intervals, ensuring that even if one key is compromised, previous and future data remains secure.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Additionally, OpenVPN can be configured with various encryption ciphers, such as ChaCha20 and AES-256.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It runs in userspace instead of requiring IP stack (therefore kernel) operation.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN has the ability to drop root privileges, use mlockall to prevent swapping sensitive data to disk, enter a chroot jail after initialization, and apply a SELinux context after initialization.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN runs a custom security protocol based on SSL and TLS, rather than supporting IKE, IPsec, L2TP or PPTP.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN supports the use of smart cards via PKCS#11-based cryptographic tokens.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN can be extended with third-party plug-ins or scripts, which can be called at defined entry points.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] The purpose of this is often to extend OpenVPN with more advanced logging, enhanced authentication with username and passwords, dynamic firewall updates, RADIUS integration and so on.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] The plug-ins are dynamically loadable modules, usually written in C, while the scripts interface can execute any scripts or binaries available to OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] In the OpenVPN source code there are some examples of such plug-ins, including a PAM authentication plug-in.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Several third-party plug-ins also exist to authenticate against LDAP or SQL databases such as SQLite and MySQL.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] This is an example for an OpenVPN control channel packet when HMAC based auth is enabled (tls-auth option in OpenVPN).
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] Data channel packets, which carry IP traffic, have a different format.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It is available on Solaris, Linux, OpenBSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, QNX, macOS and Windows XP and later.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN is available for mobile operating systems including Maemo, Windows Mobile 6.5 and below, iOS 3GS+ devices, jailbroken iOS 3.1.2+ devices, Android 4.0+ devices, and Android devices that have had the Cyanogenmod aftermarket firmware flashed or have the correct kernel module installed.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It is not compatible with some mobile phone OSes, including Palm OS.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] It is not a "web-based" VPN shown as a web page such as Citrix or Terminal Services Web access; the program is installed independently and configured by editing text files manually, rather than through a GUI-based wizard.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN is not compatible with VPN clients that use the IPsec over L2TP or PPTP protocols.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] The entire package consists of one binary for both client and server connections, an optional configuration file, and one or more key files depending on the authentication method used.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN has been integrated into several router firmware packages allowing users to run OpenVPN in client or server mode from their network routers.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] A router running OpenVPN in client mode, for example, allows any device on a network to access a VPN without needing the capability to install OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN has also been implemented in some manufacturer router firmware.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN has been integrated into SoftEther VPN, an open-source multi-protocol VPN server, to allow users to connect to the VPN server from existing OpenVPN clients.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN is also integrated into Vyos, an open-source routing operating system forked from the Vyatta software router.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] OpenVPN connections can be easily detected using deep packet inspection, based on known header data of the transmitted packets, regardless of the protocol or port used.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] While deep packet inspection does not allow determining the contents of the encrypted tunnel, it can be used to block the connection, identify communication participants, and log related data.
[src:vpn-security/openvpn] This is particularly important when the use of VPN connections is prohibited in certain environments, for example, in countries where encrypted connections are banned, or under civil legislation when circumventing network blocks in corporate networks.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] In computer networking, **split tunneling** allows a user to access distinct security domains at the same time, using the same or different network connections.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] This connection state is usually facilitated through the simultaneous use of a LAN network interface controller (NIC), radio NIC, Wireless LAN NIC, and virtual private network client software application.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] Split tunneling is most commonly configured via the use of a remote-access VPN client, which allows the user to simultaneously connect to a nearby wireless network, resources on an off-site corporate network, as well as websites over the internet.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] A split tunnel configured to only tunnel traffic destined to a specific set of destinations is called a *split-include* tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] When configured to accept all traffic except traffic destined to a specific set of destinations, it is called a *split-exclude* tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] Advantages of split tunneling include alleviating bottlenecks, conserving bandwidth (as internet traffic does not have to pass through the VPN server), and enabling a user to not have to continually connect and disconnect when remotely accessing resources..
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] Disadvantages include potentially bypassing gateway-level security that might be in place within the company infrastructure.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] Internet service providers often use split tunneling to that implement for DNS hijacking purposes.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] An "inverse" split tunnel is one that allows all datagrams to enter the tunnel, except those destination IPs explicitly allowed by VPN gateway.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] The criteria for allowing datagrams to exit the local network interface (outside the tunnel) may vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] This keeps control of network gateways to a centralized policy device such as the VPN terminator.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] This can be augmented by endpoint policy enforcement technologies such as an interface firewall on the endpoint device's network interface driver, group policy object or anti-malware agent.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] This is related in many ways to network access control (NAC).
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] A form of split-tunneling that derives the IP addresses to include/exclude at runtime-based on a list of hostname rules/policies.
[src:vpn-security/split-tunneling] Internal IPv6 content can be hosted and presented to sites via a unique local address range at the VPN level, while external IPv4 & IPv6 content can be accessed via site routers.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In computer networks, a **tunneling protocol** is a communication protocol that allows for the movement of data from one network to another.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] They can, for example, allow private communications to be sent across a public network (such as the Internet), or for one network protocol to be carried over an incompatible network, through a process called encapsulation.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Because tunneling involves repackaging the traffic data into a different form, perhaps with encryption as standard, it can hide the nature of the traffic that is run through a tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling protocols work by using the data portion of a packet (the payload) to carry the packets that actually provide the service.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling uses a layered protocol model such as those of the OSI or TCP/IP protocol suite, but usually violates the layering when using the payload to carry a service not normally provided by the network.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Typically, the delivery protocol operates at an equal or higher level in the layered model than the payload protocol.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] A tunneling protocol may, for example, allow a foreign protocol to run over a network that does not support that particular protocol, such as running IPv6 over IPv4.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Another important use is to provide services that are impractical or unsafe to be offered using only the underlying network services, such as providing a corporate network address to a remote user whose physical network address is not part of the corporate network.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Users can also use tunneling to "sneak through" a firewall, using a protocol that the firewall would normally block, but "wrapped" inside a protocol that the firewall does not block, such as HTTP.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] If the firewall policy does not specifically exclude this kind of "wrapping", this trick can function to get around the intended firewall policy (or any set of interlocked firewall policies).
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Another HTTP-based tunneling method uses the HTTP CONNECT method/command.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] A client issues the HTTP CONNECT command to an HTTP proxy.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] The proxy then makes a TCP connection to a particular server:port, and relays data between that server:port and the client connection.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Because this creates a security hole, CONNECT-capable HTTP proxies commonly restrict access to the CONNECT method.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] The proxy allows connections only to specific ports, such as 443 for HTTPS.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Other tunneling methods able to bypass network firewalls make use of different protocols such as DNS, MQTT, and SMS.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] As an example of network layer over network layer, Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE), a protocol running over IP (IP protocol number 47), often serves to carry IP packets, with RFC 1918 private addresses, over the Internet using delivery packets with public IP addresses.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In this case, the delivery and payload protocols are the same, but the payload addresses are incompatible with those of the delivery network.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] It is also possible to establish a connection using the data link layer.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] The Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) allows the transmission of frames between two nodes.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] A tunnel is not encrypted by default: the TCP/IP protocol chosen determines the level of security.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] SSH uses port 22 to enable data encryption of payloads being transmitted over a public network (such as the Internet) connection, thereby providing VPN functionality.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] IPsec has an end-to-end Transport Mode, but can also operate in a tunneling mode through a trusted security gateway.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] To understand a particular protocol stack imposed by tunneling, network engineers must understand both the payload and delivery protocol sets.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] The throughput of a TCP‑over‑TCP connection can be degraded because the control loops in the inner and outer TCPs interfere destructively with each other.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Because TCP is designed to guarantee in‑order and complete packet delivery, the outer TCP masks the connection's health from the inner TCP.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In normal TCP operation, packet loss is detected when the receiver replies with duplicate ACKs to a packet received before the missing packet in the sequence.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In response, the sender retransmits the lost packet and halves the Congestion Window (CWND).
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In TCP‑over‑TCP, the outer TCP handles lost packets normally through retransmission and CWND reduction.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Still, since the inner TCP has not received any information indicating latency in the connection, it continues to transmit packets at the rate currently governed by its CWND.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP’s CWND is greater than the outer TCP’s, the outer TCP’s send buffer eventually fills.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] As the buffer inflates, packets experience longer and more variable queueing delays before transmission, thereby increasing the outer TCP’s measured round-trip time (RTT) and RTT variability.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] This inflates its retransmission timeout (RTO).
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Once the send buffer becomes full, the tunnel process can no longer forward inner‑TCP ACKs, so the inner TCP stops receiving acknowledgments entirely.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP is no longer receiving ACKs, its RTO expires, causing it to retransmit the oldest unacknowledged segment and double its RTO.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] The inner TCP’s RTO then grows exponentially because it doubles with every timeout, and no ACKs are received to reset it.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] The result of a TCP meltdown is an outer TCP with a severely reduced CWND, an inflated RTO, and a full send buffer.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] This indicates that the inner TCP cannot write and that ACKs are not being sent in either direction.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] A *Secure Shell (SSH) tunnel* consists of an encrypted tunnel created through an SSH protocol connection.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Users may set up SSH tunnels to transfer unencrypted traffic over a network through an encrypted channel.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] It is a software-based approach to network security and the result is transparent encryption.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] For example, Microsoft Windows machines can share files using the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol, a non-encrypted protocol.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] If one were to mount a Microsoft Windows file-system remotely through the Internet, someone snooping on the connection could see transferred files.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] To mount the Windows file-system securely, one can establish a SSH tunnel that routes all SMB traffic to the remote fileserver through an encrypted channel.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Even though the SMB protocol itself contains no encryption, the encrypted SSH channel through which it travels offers security.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Once an SSH connection has been established, the tunnel starts with SSH listening to a port on the remote or local host.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Any connections to it are forwarded to the specified address and port originating from the opposing (remote or local, as previously) host.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Naturally, this wrapping and unwrapping also occurs in the reverse direction of the bidirectional tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] SSH tunnels provide a means to bypass firewalls that prohibit certain Internet services – so long as a site allows outgoing connections.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] For example, an organization may prohibit a user from accessing Internet web pages (port 80) directly without passing through the organization's proxy filter (which provides the organization with a means of monitoring and controlling what the user sees through the web).
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] But users may not wish to have their web traffic monitored or blocked by the organisation's proxy filter.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] If users can connect to an external SSH server, they can create an SSH tunnel to forward a given port on their local machine to port 80 on a remote web server.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Some SSH clients support dynamic port forwarding that allows the user to create a SOCKS 4/5 proxy.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In this case users can configure their applications to use their local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] This gives more flexibility than creating an SSH tunnel to a single port as previously described.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] SOCKS can free the user from the limitations of connecting only to a predefined remote port and server.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] If an application does not support SOCKS, a proxifier can be used to redirect the application to the local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Some proxifiers, such as Proxycap, support SSH directly, thus avoiding the need for an SSH client.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In recent versions of OpenSSH it is even allowed to create layer 2 or layer 3 tunnels if both ends have enabled such tunneling capabilities.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] This creates `tun` (layer 3, default) or `tap` (layer 2) virtual interfaces on both ends of the connection.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] This allows normal network management and routing to be used, and when used on routers, the traffic for an entire subnetwork can be tunneled.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] A pair of `tap` virtual interfaces function like an Ethernet cable connecting both ends of the connection and can join kernel bridges.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] Over the years, tunneling and data encapsulation have in very rare cases been adopted for malicious reasons, in order to maliciously communicate outside of a protected network.
[src:vpn-security/tunneling-protocol] In this context, known tunnels involve protocols such as HTTP, SSH, DNS, MQTT.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A **virtual private network** (**VPN**) is an overlay network that uses network virtualization to extend a private network across a public network, such as the Internet, via the use of encryption and tunneling protocols.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In a VPN, a tunneling protocol is used to transfer network messages from one network host to another.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Host-to-network VPNs are commonly used by organizations to allow off-site users secure access to an office network over the Internet.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs connect two networks, such as an office network and a datacenter.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Provider-provisioned VPNs isolate parts of the provider's own network infrastructure in virtual segments, in ways that make the contents of each segment private with respect to the others.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Individuals also use VPNs to encrypt and attempt to anonymize their network traffic, with VPN services selling access to their own private networks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] However, the VPN provider and the online service being accessed via the VPN may have visibility of the user's activities.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful external data sniffing attacks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A network is a group of communicating computers known as hosts, which communicate data to other hosts via communication protocols, as facilitated by networking hardware.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Within a computer network, computers are identified by network addresses, which allow rule-based systems such as Internet Protocol (IP) to locate and identify hosts.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Hosts may also have hostnames, memorable labels for the host nodes, which are rarely changed after initial assignment.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The transmission medium that supports information exchange includes wired media like copper cables, optical fibers, and wireless radio-frequency media.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The arrangement of hosts and hardware within a network architecture is known as the network topology.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A communication protocol is a set of rules for exchanging information over a network.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Communication protocols have various characteristics, such as being connection-oriented or connectionless, or using circuit switching or packet switching.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In a protocol stack, often constructed per the OSI model, communications functions are divided into protocol layers, where each layer leverages the services of the layer below it until the lowest layer controls the hardware that sends information across the media.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The use of protocol layering is ubiquitous across the field of computer networking.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] An important example of a protocol stack is HTTP, the World Wide Web protocol.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] HTTP runs over TCP over IP, the internet protocols, which in turn run over IEEE 802.11, the Wi-Fi protocol.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This stack is used between a wireless router and a personal computer when accessing the web.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Most modern computer networks use protocols based on packet-mode transmission.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A network packet is a formatted unit of data carried by a packet-switched network.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Packets consist of two types of data: control information and user data (payload).
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The control information provides data the network needs to deliver the user data, for example, source and destination network addresses, error detection codes, and sequencing information.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Typically, control information is found in packet headers and trailers, with payload data in between.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The Internet protocol suite, also called TCP/IP, is the foundation of all modern networking and the defining set of protocols for the Internet.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] It offers connection-less and connection-oriented services over an inherently unreliable network traversed by datagram transmission using Internet protocol (IP).
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] At its core, the protocol suite defines the addressing, identification, and routing specifications for Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) and for IPv6, the next generation of the protocol with a much enlarged addressing capability.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] VPNs do not make connected users anonymous or unidentifiable to the untrusted medium network provider, such as an Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] However, VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful data sniffing attacks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Data packets travelling across a VPN may also be secured by tamper proofing via a message authentication code, prevents the message from being altered or tampered without being rejected, enhancing data integrity.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A number of other implementations exist to ensure authentication of connecting parties.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Tunnel endpoints can be authenticated in various ways during the VPN access initiation, such as by the whitelisting of endpoint IP address.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Authentication may also occur after actual tunnels are already active, for example, with a web captive portal.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Remote-access VPNs may also use passwords, biometrics, two-factor authentication, or other cryptographic methods.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs often use passwords (pre-shared keys) or digital certificates.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling allows a user to access distinct security domains at the same time, using the same or different network connections.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Disadvantages include DNS leaks and potentially bypassing gateway-level security that might be in place within the company infrastructure.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A *host-to-network* configuration is analogous to joining one or more computers to a network to which they cannot be directly connected.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This type of extension provides computer access to a local area network of a remote site, or any wider enterprise networks, such as an intranet.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Each computer is in charge of activating its own tunnel towards the network it wants to join.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The joined network is only aware of a single remote host for each tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This may be employed for remote workers, or to enable people accessing their private home or company resources without exposing them on the public Internet.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A *site-to-site* configuration connects two networks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This configuration expands a network across geographically disparate locations.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Tunneling is only done between gateway devices located at each network location.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] These devices then make the tunnel available to other local network hosts that aim to reach any host on the other side.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This is useful to keep sites connected to each other in a stable manner, like office networks to their headquarters or datacenter.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In this case, any side may be configured to initiate the communication as long as it knows how to reach the other.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In the context of site-to-site configurations, the terms *intranet* and *extranet* are used to describe two different use cases.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] An *intranet* site-to-site VPN describes a configuration where the sites connected by the VPN belong to the same organization, whereas an *extranet* site-to-site VPN joins sites belonging to multiple organizations.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support broadcast domains.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Therefore, communication, software, and networking that are based on layer 2 and broadcast packets (such as NetBIOS used in Windows networking) may not be fully supported as on a local area network.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Variants on VPN such as Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Trusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead, they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) often overlays trusted VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A secure VPN either trusts the underlying delivery network or enforces security with an internal mechanism.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Mobile VPNs are widely used in public safety where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as computer-assisted dispatch and criminal databases, and in other organizations with similar requirements such as field service management and healthcare.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network (DMVPN) is a dynamic tunneling form of a virtual private network supported on Cisco IOS-based routers, Huawei AR G3 routers, and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] DMVPN provides the capability for creating a dynamic-mesh VPN network without having to statically pre-configure all possible tunnel end-point peers, such as IPsec and ISAKMP peers.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] DMVPN is initially configured to build a hub-and-spoke network by statically configuring the hubs (VPN headends) on the spokes; no change in the configuration on the hub is required to accept new spokes.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Using this initial hub-and-spoke network, tunnels between spokes are dynamically built on demand without additional configuration on the hubs or spokes.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This dynamic-mesh capability alleviates the need for any load on the hub to route data between the spoke networks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Ethernet VPN (EVPN) is a technology for carrying OSI layer 2 Ethernet traffic as a virtual private network using wide area network protocols.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) is a routing technique in telecommunications networks that directs data from one node to the next based on labels rather than network addresses.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Whereas network addresses identify endpoints, MPLS labels identify established paths between endpoints.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] MPLS can encapsulate packets of various network protocols.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service Ethernet traffic.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) is a virtual private network technology that provides Ethernet-based multipoint-to-multipoint communication over IP or MPLS networks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] It allows geographically dispersed sites to share an Ethernet broadcast domain by connecting sites (including both servers and clients) through pseudowires.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The technologies that can be used as pseudo-wire can be Ethernet over MPLS, L2TPv3 or even GRE.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] There are two IETF standards-track RFCs (RFC 4761 and RFC 4762) describing VPLS establishment.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In contrast to L2TPv3, which allows only point-to-point OSI layer 2 tunnels, VPLS allows any-to-any (multipoint) connectivity.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A virtual private network is based on a tunneling protocol, and may be combined with other network or application protocols to provide additional security and capabilities.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) is a standards-based security protocol, initially developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for IPv6, and was required in all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The design of IPSec meets most security goals: availability, integrity, and confidentiality.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] IPsec is also often supported by network hardware accelerators, which makes IPsec VPN desirable for low-power scenarios, like always-on remote access VPN configurations.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels are set up by the Internet Key Exchange (IKE) protocol.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels made with IKE version 1 (also known as IKEv1 tunnels, or often just "IPsec tunnels") can be used alone to provide VPN but are often combined with the Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) to reuse existing L2TP-related implementations for more flexible authentication features (e.g.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] IKE version 2, which was created by Microsoft and Cisco, can be used alone to provide IPsec VPN functionality.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Its primary advantages are the native support for authenticating via the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) and that the tunnel can be seamlessly restored when the IP address of the associated host is changing, which is typical of a roaming mobile device, whether on 3G or 4G LTE networks.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the OpenVPN project and SoftEther VPN project) or secure an individual connection.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through TLS.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] A VPN based on TLS can connect from locations where the usual TLS web navigation (HTTPS) is supported without requiring additional configuration.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH offers VPN tunneling (distinct from port forwarding) to secure remote connections to a network, inter-network links, and remote systems.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] SSH is more often used to remotely connect to machines or networks instead of a site to site VPN connection.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] OpenVPN is a free and open-source VPN protocol based on the TLS protocol.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] It supports perfect forward-secrecy, and most modern secure cipher suites, like AES, Serpent, TwoFish, etc.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] It is currently being developed and updated by OpenVPN Inc., a non-profit providing secure VPN technologies.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol (SSTP) is a form of VPN tunnel that provides a mechanism to transport Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) traffic through an SSL/TLS channel.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] WireGuard is a protocol designed to be more lightweight than OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In 2020, WireGuard support was added to both the Linux and Android kernels, opening it up to adoption by VPN providers.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] By default, WireGuard utilizes the Curve25519 protocol for key exchange and ChaCha20-Poly1305 for encryption and message authentication, but also includes the ability to pre-share a symmetric key between the client and server.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Desktop, smartphone and other end-user device operating systems usually support configuring remote access VPN from their graphical or command-line tools.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] However, due to the variety of, often non standard, VPN protocols, there exist many third-party applications that implement additional protocols not yet or no longer natively supported by the OS.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] For instance, Android lacked native IPsec IKEv2 support until version 11, and users needed to install third-party apps in order to connect that kind of VPN.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Conversely, Windows does not natively support plain IPsec IKEv1 remote access native VPN configuration (commonly used by Cisco and Fritz!Box VPN solutions).
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Network appliances, such as firewalls, often include VPN gateway functionality for either remote access or site-to-site configurations.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Their administration interfaces often facilitate setting up virtual private networks with a selection of supported protocols.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In some cases, like in the open source operating systems devoted to firewalls and network devices (like OpenWrt, IPFire, PfSense or OPNsense), it is possible to add support for additional VPN protocols by installing missing software components or third-party apps.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Commercial appliances with VPN features based on proprietary hardware or software platforms usually support a consistent VPN protocol across their products, but do not allow customizations outside the use cases they implement.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] This is often the case for appliances that rely on hardware acceleration of VPNs to provide higher throughput or support a larger number of simultaneously connected users.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] According to a 2022 estimate, 3% of Chinese netizens use VPNs, compared to 8.5% of Americans.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] In China, VPNs are increasingly blocked and unauthorized usage can be subject to fines and legal prosecution.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Based on its estimates of leaked government documents, ChinaFile estimated in 2026 that VPN demand in China was in the low single digits.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] It also estimated that foreign apps blocked by the Great Firewall have extremely low traffic, particularly compared to domestic apps; the top five domestic apps saw traffic that was 1,000 times more than the top five foreign apps.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] As of 2025, approximately 1.75 billion people used VPNs.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] By 2027, this market is projected to grow to $76 billion.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] Amid Internet restrictions and blocking in Russia, Internet activists created the Amnezia VPN project in 2020 during a digital rights hackathon organized by Roskomsvoboda.
[src:vpn-security/virtual-private-network] The service gained popularity among Russian users by providing access to blocked resources, as well as features aimed at enhancing anonymity and resistance to traffic analysis.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In March 2020, the Linux version of the software reached a stable production release and was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 kernel, and backported to earlier Linux kernels in some Linux distributions.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The Linux kernel components are licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL) version 2; other implementations are under GPLv2 or other free/open-source licenses.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The WireGuard protocol is a variant of the Noise Protocol Framework `IK` handshake pattern.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The key exchange, or handshake, combines long-term and ephemeral Diffie-Hellman values using Curve25519.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Each pair generates a set of public and private key pairs using Curve 25519, the public keys are exchanged, with each pair then assigned an IP address (generally RFC 1918) to utilize with the WireGuard tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Once the keys have been confirmed by both peers, the Noise Protocol is used to generate a shared ChaCha20 session key for symmetric encryption authenticated with Poly1305.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] SipHash24 is used for hashtable keys while BLAKE2s cryptographic hash functions, a faster and more compact version of SHA-3, are incorporated.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Key derivation functions are handled using HKDF and Base64-encoded private keys, public keys and preshared keys.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] WireGuard’s proof starts by modeling its two-message Noise-based handshake (plus optional PSK) in CryptoVerif’s calculus of cryptographic games, abstracting ChaCha20-Poly1305, Curve25519, HKDF, the hash chain, and related primitives under standard IND-CPA/INT-CTXT and random-oracle assumptions.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] From that model, CryptoVerif’s automated game hops show, across unlimited parallel sessions, that the protocol guarantees mutual authentication, IND-CCA session-key secrecy, forward secrecy and post-compromise security even if long-term keys later leak and state is wiped.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In May 2019, researchers from INRIA published a machine-checked proof of the WireGuard protocol, produced using the CryptoVerif proof assistant.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] WireGuard supports pre-shared symmetric key mode, which provides an additional layer of symmetric encryption to mitigate future advances in quantum computing.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] This addresses the risk that traffic may be stored until quantum computers are capable of breaking Curve25519, at which point traffic could be decrypted.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Pre-shared keys are "usually troublesome from a key management perspective and might be more likely stolen", but in the shorter term, if the symmetric key is compromised, the Curve25519 keys still provide more than sufficient protection.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] WireGuard uses only UDP, due to the potential disadvantages of TCP-over-TCP.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Tunneling TCP over a TCP-based connection can induce a dramatic loss in transmission performance due to the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] WireGuard fully supports IPv6, both inside and outside of tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] It supports only layer 3 for both IPv4 and IPv6 and can encapsulate v4-in-v6 and vice versa.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Assuming the underlay network transporting the WireGuard packets maintains a 1500 byte MTU, configuring the WireGuard interface to 1420 bytes MTU for all involved peers is ideal for being transported over IPv6 + IPv4.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] However, when exclusively utilizing legacy IPv4 transport, a higher MTU of 1440 bytes for the WireGuard interface suffices.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] From an operational perspective and for network configuration uniformity, leaving the default 1420 byte MTU network-wide for the WireGuard interfaces would be advantageous.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] This approach ensures consistency and facilitates a smoother transition to enabling IPv6 for the WireGuard peers and interfaces in the future.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Hosts often avoid sending packets > 1280 due to PMTUD reliability.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The MTU of a WireGuard interface is determined by the encapsulating, or *outer*, IP protocol—not the IP version carried inside the tunnel.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] When WireGuard packets are transported over IPv4, the outer-header overhead is 60 bytes (20-byte IPv4 header, 8-byte UDP header, and 32-byte WireGuard header).
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] When transported over IPv6, the outer-header overhead rises to 80 bytes.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] This distinction means that even if a peer is reachable only via IPv4, other peers in the same mesh may connect over IPv6 or through translation mechanisms.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Translation increases header size and enforces IPv6’s 1280-byte minimum path MTU, requiring that implementers budget for the 80-byte IPv6 overhead when setting a consistent interface MTU.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] WireGuard is designed to be extended by third-party programs and scripts.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] This has been used to augment WireGuard with various features including more user-friendly management interfaces (including easier setting up of keys), logging, dynamic firewall updates, dynamic IP assignment, and LDAP integration.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] It is supported natively and by a number of commercial VPN services such as NordVPN, IPVanish, Mullvad, and TunnelBear.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] One WireGuard-based fork, AmneziaWG, adds traffic-obfuscation mechanisms intended to make WireGuard traffic less identifiable to deep packet inspection systems.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Excluding such complex features from the minimal core codebase improves its stability and security.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] For ensuring security, WireGuard restricts the options for implementing cryptographic controls, limits the choices for key exchange processes, and maps algorithms to a small subset of modern cryptographic primitives.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] If a flaw is found in any of the primitives, a new version can be released that resolves the issue.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] A review by *Ars Technica* found that WireGuard was easy to set up and use, used strong ciphers, and had a minimal codebase that provided for a small attack surface.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] A 2024 report concluded that WireGuard had potential as a lightweight robust solution for Internet of things security.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] WireGuard has received funding from the Open Technology Fund and donations from *Jump Trading*, Mullvad, Tailscale, *Fly.io*, and the NLnet Foundation.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Oregon senator Ron Wyden has recommended to the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) that they evaluate WireGuard as a replacement for existing technologies.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Early snapshots of the code base exist from 30 June 2016.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The logo is inspired by a stone engraving of the mythological Python that Jason Donenfeld saw while visiting a museum in Delphi.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 9 December 2019, David Miller – primary maintainer of the Linux networking stack – accepted the WireGuard patches into the "net-next" maintainer tree, for inclusion in an upcoming kernel.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 28 January 2020, Linus Torvalds merged David Miller's net-next tree, and WireGuard entered the mainline Linux kernel tree.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 20 March 2020, Debian developers enabled the module build options for WireGuard in their kernel config for the Debian 11 version (testing).
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 29 March 2020 WireGuard was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 release tree.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The Windows version of the software remains at beta.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] This led to Android developers adding native kernel support for WireGuard in their Generic Kernel Image on 30 March 2020.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 22 April 2020, NetworkManager developer Beniamino Galvani merged GUI support for WireGuard in GNOME.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 12 May 2020, Matt Dunwoodie proposed patches for native kernel support of WireGuard in OpenBSD.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 22 June 2020, after the work of Matt Dunwoodie and Jason A.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Donenfeld, WireGuard support was imported into OpenBSD.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Donenfeld released an update of the Windows package improving installation, stability, ARM support, and enterprise features.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 29 November 2020, WireGuard support was imported into the FreeBSD 13 kernel.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] On 19 January 2021, WireGuard support was added for preview in pfSense Community Edition (CE) 2.5.0 development snapshots.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In March 2021, kernel-mode WireGuard support was removed from FreeBSD 13.0, still in testing, after an urgent code cleanup in FreeBSD WireGuard could not be completed quickly.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] FreeBSD-based pfSense Community Edition (CE) 2.5.0 and pfSense Plus 21.02 removed kernel-based WireGuard as well.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In May 2021, WireGuard support was re-introduced back into pfSense CE and pfSense Plus development snapshots as an experimental package written by a member of the pfSense community, Christian McDonald.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] The WireGuard package for pfSense incorporates the ongoing kernel-mode WireGuard development work by Jason A.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] Donenfeld that was originally sponsored by Netgate.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In June 2021, the official package repositories for both pfSense CE 2.5.2 and pfSense Plus 21.05 included the WireGuard package.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In 2023, WireGuard received over 209,000€ support from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In June 2025, IPFire has added support for WireGuard using the Linux kernel implementation.
[src:vpn-security/wireguard] In January 2026 Iran International reported that WireGuard was being used in Iran in the aftermath of the 2026 Iran protests, albeit with limited success.
